## post 1 
"How do I know if my ideal customers are on YouTube?"

It's simple...

95% of the time, they are.

It's the 2nd biggest search engine on the planet. (after Google)

Your buyers go there to learn, to compare, to solve problems before they ever talk to a salesperson or sign up.

So the real question isn't "are they there?"

It's "how many of them are there, and what should I expect?"

That's where most B2B companies go wrong.

They see some creator getting 500k views per video and that's what they measure themselves against.

But you're not selling to a B2C audience.

You're selling to a very specific kind of B2B buyer.

Maybe it's heads of sales at 50+ employee companies.

Maybe it's agency owners doing 7 figures.

There are simply fewer of those people than there are folks searching "how to make money with dropshipping."

So no, you won't get 500k views on videos.

You might get 5k.

You might get 60k.

You might get 400.

It all depends on the size of your TAM, and that is completely fine.

Because 400 of the exact right people will generate you more revenue than 500k views from teenagers who want to get rich quick.

We have clients generating leads every week off videos with a few 100 views.

Now there's one case where you can't generate leads on YouTube:

If your ICP is so specific that only a few 1,000 people on earth actually fit it, YouTube probably won't hand you organic leads every week.

There just isn't enough search demand to ride.

But that doesn't mean you shouldn't do YouTube.

You just use it differently:

- You make videos that prove you know your stuff

- Then you put them in front of the leads you're already in conversations with

(Before a sales call, inside a follow-up, on your website)

That alone can move your close rate, because the prospect shows up already trusting you and this gives you the ROI.

For maybe 5% of B2B businesses, that's the play.

For the other 95%, YouTube can become one of the best lead sources they have.

The whole game is knowing which one you are before you start.

And developing your strategy based on that.

