## post 3 

Taylor Haren books 30+ calls a month from YouTube.

But when I asked him what actually made it work, he didn't say scripts, thumbnails, or edits.

He said something most businesses never think about.

That the editing, the SEO, the packaging... those are just checkboxes.

Of course they need to be good.

But every decent agency can get those right.

They're the price of entry, not the thing that wins.

The question he kept coming back to was a different one:

Can I actually fit this into how I already run my company?

And can I keep doing it long enough for it to pay off?

Because that's where almost everyone fails on YouTube.

They go all in for 1-2 months, burn out, and they stop before the channel ever has a chance to compound.

YouTube doesn't reward the person who makes 1 really good video.

It rewards the one who sticks with it.

That's the only way it can turn into a lead generating machine, like it did for Taylor.

So before you stress about your edits or your thumbnails...

Ask yourself the question Taylor did:

Is this something I'll still be doing 12 months from now?

If the answer is no, fix that first.

Find a partner who can make it sustainable for you forever.

Everything else is just a checkbox.